# React Native UI Don'ts

## Don't: Wrap the whole screen in TouchableOpacity that dismisses keyboard

**Problem:** Wrapping a screen (including TextInputs) in `TouchableOpacity` with `onPress={Keyboard.dismiss}` causes text inputs to lose focus immediately when tapped. The tap both focuses the input and triggers the parent's `onPress`, which dismisses the keyboard and unfocuses the input.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD - User cannot type; input focus is stolen
<TouchableOpacity onPress={() => Keyboard.dismiss()} style={styles.container}>
  <TextInput ... />
</TouchableOpacity>
```

**Fix:** Use a plain `View` as the root. Use `ScrollView`'s `keyboardDismissMode="on-drag"` for tap-outside-to-dismiss behavior, or wrap only non-interactive background areas in a separate TouchableOpacity (not the form).

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
<View style={styles.container}>
  <ScrollView keyboardDismissMode="on-drag">
    <TextInput ... />
  </ScrollView>
</View>
```

## Don't: Leave invisible layout space when components dismiss

**Problem:** When a component fades out (e.g. `Animated.View` with `opacity: 0`) or is hidden, it still occupies layout space if you only set `opacity` or `display: 'none'`. This creates "dead space" — blank areas where nothing is visible but layout is reserved.

**Fix:** When a component is dismissed/hidden, return `null` so it is removed from the layout entirely. Do this after the animation completes (in the `Animated.timing().start()` callback).
